      "id": "ec001-sp-062",
      "campaign_id": "EC-2026-001",
      "platform": "Instagram",
      "hook": "The chicken that expired. The salad kit. The berries. Not your fault.",
      "body_copy": "You bought it with good intentions. You had a plan. Then Tuesday became chaos, Wednesday was takeout, and Thursday you found it again — spoiled.\n\n$111 every month. That's what gets thrown away in the average household. Food that was supposed to be dinner but never made it to the table.\n\nThe organic strawberries you were going to put in smoothies. The fresh herbs for that recipe you bookmarked. The ground turkey that was going to be three different meals. All of it, gone.\n\nIt's not because you don't care. It's not because you're wasteful. It's because the gap between buying food and actually cooking it is where everything falls apart.\n\nYou shop with hope. You come home with bags full of possibility. Then life happens. Kids need help with homework. Work runs late. Someone gets sick. The fresh food sits there, waiting for a moment that never comes.\n\n$1,336 a year. Money that could be vacation funds, college savings, or that kitchen renovation you've been putting off. Instead, it's in your compost bin.\n\nThe system is broken. Shopping and cooking exist in two different worlds, and you're stuck in the gap between them.",
